1. Open raster dataset as MDim Raster¶

currently support netcdf, mdim CRF and multidimensional mosaic dataset as input

Properties¶

* isMultidimensional
* mdinfo
* slices
* variables
* variableNames

Methods¶

* getVariableAttributes(variable_name)
* getDimensionNames(variable_name)
* getDimensionAttributes(variable_name, dimension_name)
* getDimensionValues(variable_name, dimension_name)
* save({name})

2. new functions in arcpy.ia¶

  • Subset
  • Aggregate
  • Apply

2.1. Subset(in_raster, {variables}, {dimension_definitions})¶

https://pro.arcgis.com/en/pro-app/arcpy/image-analyst/subset.htm

Filter the mdim raster along variables or/and dimensions.
The paramter variables supports single variable name or a list of variable names

  • varialbes = varaible_name
  • variables = [variable_name,...]

The parameter dimension_definitions support dict input as below

  • {dimension_name: value, ...}
  • {dimension_name: (min, max),...}
  • {dimension_name:[value1, (min1, max1), …], ...}
  • {dimension_name:(from, to, recurrent_interval_size, recurrent_interval_unit), ...}
    • recurrently select single slice if to = None
    • otherwise, it means recurrently select ranges

Case 1. filter variables only¶

In [9]:
# select all slices of the two variables surface elevation and water temperature 
out_raster1 = arcpy.ia.Subset(myRaster, variables = ['surf_el', 'water_temp']) 
out_raster1.variables
Out[9]:
['surf_el(StdTime=57)', 'water_temp(StdTime=57, StdZ=40)']

Case 2. filter dimensions: {dimension_name: value, ...}¶

In [11]:
# filter those variables that have dimension depth, only choose their slice(s) at depth=0.
# For those variables that do not have dimension depth, all slices would be selected 
out_raster2 = arcpy.ia.Subset(myRaster, dimension_definitions = {'StdZ':0})   
# verify the depth values in the variabiable are zero or not
out_raster2.getDimensionValues('salinity', 'StdZ')
Out[11]:
[0.0]

2.2. Aggregate(in_raster, dimension_name, raster_function, {raster_function_arguments}, {aggregation_definition})¶

https://pro.arcgis.com/en/pro-app/arcpy/image-analyst/aggregate.htm

Aggregate mdim raster based on user specified dimension intervals and aggregation method
The paramter aggregation_def defines how slices are grouped

  • {"interval": interval_keyword}
    • interval_keyword includes hourly, daily, weekly, monthly, yearly
  • {"interval_value": value, "interval_unit": unit}
  • {"interval_ranges": [(min,max),(min,max), ...]}
  • {"recurrent_interval": recurrent_keyword}
    • recurrent_keyword includes quarterly, monthly, weekly, daily
In [18]:
arcpy.CheckOutExtension("ImageAnalyst")
Out[18]:
'NotLicensed'
In [19]:
in_raster_path = r"\\pa\raster\dataswap\kaixi\compression_data\prcp_1980.nc"
# load the raster dataset as a mdim raster
prcpRaster=arcpy.Raster(in_raster_path, True)
prcpRaster.variables
Out[19]:
['prcp(StdTime=365)']

Case 1. aggregate along the whole dimension ranges¶

In [21]:
# calc the average precipitation in 1980
avg_prcp = arcpy.ia.Aggregate(prcpRaster, 'StdTime', 'Mean')
avg_prcp.variables
Out[21]:
['prcp(StdTime=1)']

Case 2. aggregation_definition = {"interval" = interval_keyword}¶

In [24]:
# calc the average monthly precipitation in 1980
monthly_avg_prcp = arcpy.ia.Aggregate(prcpRaster, 'StdTime', 'Mean', aggregation_definition = {"recurrent_interval":'monthly'})
monthly_avg_prcp.variables
Out[24]:
['prcp(StdTime=12)']

2.3. Apply(in_raster, raster_function, {raster_function_arguments})¶

https://pro.arcgis.com/en/pro-app/arcpy/image-analyst/apply.htm

apply a builtin raster function or customized python raster function, or function chain to single raster or several rasters. It works with multidimensional as well as non-multidimensional raster(s)
the parameter in_raster has 4 different fomats

  • single raster
    • for those functions that need one raster input, e.g., NDVI
  • (raster1, raster2)
    • for those functions that have 2 raster inputs: Raster and Raster2, e.g., Arithmetic
  • [raster1, raster2, …]
    • for those functions that need an array of raster inputs: Rasters, e.g.,CompositeBand
  • {var_name1: raster1, var_name2: raster2, …}
    • for those functions that need a set of named raster inputs, e.g., HeatIndex

the paramter raster_function could be a built-in raster function name or a function template (.rft.xml)

Case 1. in_raster = raster¶

In [35]:
# load a multi-band raster dataset
in_raster1 = arcpy.Raster(r"\\pa\raster\DataSwap\Kaixi\Landsat\Input_LandsatImage.tif") 
# calc NDVI
out_ndvi_raster = arcpy.ia.Apply(in_raster1, 'NDVI', {'VisibleBandID':3,'InfraredBandID':4, 'ScientificOutput': True})

Visualization¶

In [37]:
rendered_ndvi_raster = arcpy.ia.Render(out_ndvi_raster, rendering_rule = {"min": 0, "max": 0.9}, colormap = "NDVI")
rendered_ndvi_raster
Out[37]:

Case 2. in_raster = (raster1, raster2)¶

In [38]:
# add the raster 
out_Arithmetic_raster = arcpy.ia.Apply((out_ndvi_raster, 2), r'\\pa\raster\dataswap\kaixi\mdim_output\Arithmetic.rft.xml')

Case 3. in_raster = [raster1, raster2, …]¶

In [40]:
folder = r"\\pa\raster\DataSwap\Kaixi\toGao\Landsat7\x10y35\2000\ls7_gm_nbart_10_-35_20000101_"
in_raster1 = folder+"blue.tif"
in_raster2 = folder+"green.tif"
in_raster3 = folder+"red.tif"
out_composite_raster = arcpy.ia.Apply([in_raster1, in_raster2, in_raster3], 'CompositeBand') 
# check band count
out_composite_raster.bandCount
Out[40]:
3

Case 4. in_raster = {var_name1: raster1, var_name2: raster2, …}¶

In [2]:
# load the grib file as a multidimensional raster
temp = arcpy.Raster(r"C:\DemoData\analysis\ds.temp.bin", True) 

# load the grib file as a mdim raster
rh = arcpy.Raster(r"C:\DemoData\analysis\ds.rhm.bin", True)
In [3]:
# apply heatindex function to two mdim raster, the output is a mdim raster ,each slice is the heat_index at a certain time point
heat_index_raster= arcpy.ia.Apply({'temperature': temp, 'rh': rh}, 'HeatIndex', {'units':'Kelvin', 'outUnits':'Fahrenheit', 'matchVariable': 0})
heat_index_raster.variables # the variable name changed to *
Out[3]:
['*(StdTime=18)']
